plicated and contradictory terrain while moving the field of communication in a more intellectually productive direction. An outstanding group of contributors from a range of academic backgrounds challenges traditional definitions and applications of rhetoric. From the troubling media representations of black looters after Hurricane Katrina and rhetoric in news coverage about the Columbine and Virginia Tech massacres to cinematic representations of race in Crash, Blood Diamond, and Quentin Tarantino's films, these essays reveal complex intersections and constructions of racialized bodies and discourses, critiquing race in innovative and exciting ways. Critical Rhetorics of Race seeks not only to understand and navigate a world fraught with racism, but to change it, one word at a time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aRacism in mass media. 0aRacism in motion pictures. 0aRacism in popular culture. 0aRacism in sports. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aLacy, Michael G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814765296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814765296.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK